Good call — CLI and server are where the data integrity bugs live. That drops us to ~47 test files with the highest ROI.

## Section 3: Testing Patterns

### Fixtures

Test fixtures in `cli/src/__fixtures__/`:

```
cli/src/__fixtures__/
├── sessions/
│   ├── claude-code-simple.jsonl    # Minimal valid session
│   ├── claude-code-complex.jsonl   # Multi-tool, long session
│   ├── malformed.jsonl             # Bad JSON lines
│   └── empty.jsonl                 # Empty file
├── config/
│   ├── valid-config.json           # Standard config
│   └── minimal-config.json         # Bare minimum
└── db/
    └── seed.ts                     # Helper to seed in-memory SQLite
```

### Database Testing

Use real in-memory SQLite (`better-sqlite3` with `:memory:`) rather than mocking. This tests actual SQL queries against a real engine:

```typescript
// db/seed.ts
import Database from 'better-sqlite3';
import { applyMigrations } from '../db/migrate.js';

export function createTestDb() {
  const db = new Database(':memory:');
  applyMigrations(db);
  return db;
}
```

### Server Route Testing

Use Hono's `app.request()` — no HTTP server needed:

```typescript
const res = await app.request('/api/sessions?project=my-project');
expect(res.status).toBe(200);
const data = await res.json();
expect(data.sessions).toHaveLength(3);
```

### Filesystem Mocking

For providers, use `vi.mock('fs')` with controlled return values rather than real filesystem access. JSONL parser tests can use fixture files read at test time.

### The "Hono Bug" Test

A dedicated import validation test that would have caught v3.0.2's bug:

```typescript
// cli/src/__tests__/package-imports.test.ts
test('server-dist entry point resolves all imports', async () => {
  // Verify that the server module can be imported without missing deps
  await expect(import('../../server-dist/index.js')).resolves.toBeDefined();
});
```

